TOP(1)                           User Commands                          TOP(1)

NAME
       top - display processes

SYNOPSIS
       top [OPTION]...

DESCRIPTION
       The  top  program  provides  a  dynamic  real-time  view  of  a
       running system.  It can display system summary information as
       well as a list of processes currently being managed by the kernel.

OPTIONS
       -b, --batch
              starts top in batch mode, useful for sending output from
              top to other programs or to a file

       -c, --cmdline
              toggle full command line display (show program arguments)

       -d, --delay=SECS
              specifies the delay between screen updates (default 3.0)

       -E, --scale-summary-mem=SCALE
              scale summary area memory display; SCALE is one of:
              k (KiB), m (MiB, default), g (GiB), t (TiB), p (PiB), e (EiB)

       -e, --scale-task-mem=SCALE
              scale task area memory display; SCALE is one of:
              k (KiB, default), m (MiB), g (GiB), t (TiB), p (PiB), e (EiB)

       -H, --threads
              show individual threads

       -i, --idle
              toggle idle processes display (hide idle by default with
              this flag)

       -n, --iterations=NUMBER
              maximum number of iterations (refreshes) before ending

       -o, --sort-field=FIELD
              sort by FIELD; prefix with + for descending (default) or
              - for ascending.  Fields: pid, user, pri, ni, virt, res,
              shr, s, cpu, mem, time, command

       -O, --list-fields
              print the available sort field names and exit

       -p, --pid=PID[,PID...]
              monitor only processes with the specified PIDs

       -S, --cumulative
              toggle cumulative time mode

       -s, --secure
              run in secure mode

       -U, --filter-user=USER
              show only processes with a user name or UID matching USER

       -u, --filter-user-only=USER
              show only processes with effective user name matching USER

       -V, --version
              display version information and exit

       -w, --width=COLS
              override screen width detection

       -1, --single-cpu
              toggle single/separate CPU states display

       --help display this help and exit

INTERACTIVE COMMANDS
       When top is running interactively, the following single-key
       commands are recognized:

       SPACE, RETURN
              refresh display immediately

       q      quit

       h, ?   display help

       k      kill a process (prompts for PID and signal)

       r      renice a process (prompts for PID and value)

       d, s   change delay interval (prompts for value)

       n, #   change number of processes shown

       u, U   filter by user (prompts for username)

       o, O   change sort field (prompts for field name)

       R      toggle sort direction

       f      toggle full command line display

       c      toggle command name / command line display

       S      toggle cumulative mode

       H      toggle threads mode

       i      toggle idle processes display

       B      toggle bold highlighting

       x      toggle sort column highlight

       y      toggle running task highlight

       z      toggle color/mono mode

       l      toggle load average display

       t      toggle task/CPU states display

       m      toggle memory display

       1      toggle single CPU/all CPUs display

       E      cycle summary memory scale (KiB → MiB → GiB → ...)

       e      cycle task memory scale

       W      write configuration (not currently saved)

       <, >   change sort column left/right

       Up/Down, PgUp/PgDn, Home/End
              navigate the process list

EXIT STATUS
       0      normal exit via 'q' or after -n iterations

       1      if errors occurred

